Note that this restriction applies to client-server interactions, not to server-server interactions.</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">In the case of Sparnatural, </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><u>it is the HTML page that sends the SPARQL query directly to a SPARQL service</u></span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">is SPARQL service thus needs to allow clients/webpages to send queries to it even if they are loaded from another domain, otherwise the query will simply fail with a security warning, and you can see security errors in the requests of your browser console.</span></p><p
